instance RabbitMQMessageBroker : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Message broker enabling communication between controller, low-level driver, and digital twin"
    DTDFVocab:enables DataTransmissionService, RemoteControlService
]

instance DataTransmissionService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Real-time visualization of incubator status via dashboard anomaly detection and heatbed state estimation via Kalman filter"
]

instance RemoteControlService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "On-demand calibration using Model B what-if simulations using co-simulations with historical/real-time data"
]


instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "Control commands (temperature setpoints, fan/heatbed activation) are sent from the Digital Twin to the RabbitMQ server, then to the controller. Command formats include structured messages with parameters (H, C, LL, UL). Validation ensures commands stay within safe temperature bounds. Feedback systems use sensor data for closed-loop control. Conflict resolution is handled via safe protocols in the low-level driver. Command execution confirmation is achieved through status messages and state updates in the controller statechart."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "Real-time synchronization via RabbitMQ with message brokers supporting high-frequency data exchange (tens of thousands of users). Kalman filter operates in real-time for anomaly detection and heatbed state estimation. Controller parameters (H, C) define time-based actuation durations. Simulation models predict thermal inertia with time-scale approximations, and self-adaptation loops enable dynamic recalibration based on real-time data."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "Integrated architecture with RabbitMQ as the communication backbone, connecting controller, low-level driver, and simulation models. Kalman filter and what-if simulations are embedded for state estimation and optimization. Self-adaptation loop closes the DT loop by dynamically recalibrating Model B and controller parameters. Components share data via message queues with explicit time-series database integration for visualization."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin lifecycle includes development stages: modeling (thermal dynamics with Model B), calibration (using RabbitMQ FMU and Kalman filter), real-time monitoring (dashboard visualization), and self-adaptation (loop closure via anomaly detection, experiment scheduling, and controller reconfiguration). Representation types transition from simulation models (Model A/B) to real-time data streams. Governance involves open-source version control (GitHub) and continuous calibration updates."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity: Model B (4 parameters) achieves 6°C max discrepancy vs 7°C for Model A. Validation: calibration experiments (18V fan test), Kalman filter correlation with non-measured heatbed temp. Uncertainty: sensor placement (T2/T3 positioning), environmental factors (airflow). Error correction: Kalman filter for state estimation, model re-calibration after plant behavior changes. QA: real-time data validation, self-adaptation loop (experiment scheduling, parameter updates)."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "Communication protocols: RabbitMQ (AMQP) for message brokering. Network topology: Edge (Raspberry Pi) <-> Cloud/On-premise servers. Bandwidth requirements: Lightweight for real-time data (≤100 Mbps). Latency: <100ms for critical control signals. Reliability: Message acknowledgments and retries. Security: TLS encryption for RabbitMQ (implied by open-source maturity). Redundancy: Dual-node deployment for RabbitMQ in production environments."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "Hosting platforms: Edge (Raspberry Pi 4 Model B) and cloud/on-premise servers. Computational requirements: Raspberry Pi (ARM Cortex-A53, 1.5GHz). Storage: Time-series database for logged sensor data. Scalability: Modular architecture supports additional sensors/actuators. Deployment models: Hybrid edge-cloud for real-time control and analytics. Availability: 99.9% SLA via redundant RabbitMQ nodes and failover mechanisms."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "Leverages open-source RabbitMQ for internal communication and interoperability with external systems via message brokers. Open-source hardware/software ecosystem enables integration with third-party tools. Data exchange follows MQTT/AMQP protocols through RabbitMQ. No explicit mention of enterprise system integration, but open-source availability suggests potential for external system interoperability."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "Complies with IEEE standards (e.g., [4,5,15]) and open-source protocols (RabbitMQ, SciPy). Interoperability is achieved via Functional Mock-up Units (FMUs) and Python-based simulation tools. Certification requirements include open-source availability and adherence to CPS modeling frameworks (e.g., Modelica for simulation)."
]